	h5 Inverse Hyperbolic Functions
	p From the graphs of the hyperbolic functions, we see that all of them are one-to-one except #[+m \cosh x] and #[+m \text{sech} \, x]. If we restrict the domains of these two functions to the interval #[+m [0,\infty)], then all the hyperbolic functions are one-to-one, and we can define the #[strong inverse hyperbolic functions]. Since the hyperbolic functions themselves involve exponential functions, the inverse hyperbolic functions involve logarithmic functions.
	h5 Definition
	p Inverse Hyperbolic Functions:  #[+m \begin{array}{cccc}\sinh^{-1} x=\text{arcsinh } x=\ln(x+\sqrt{x^2+1})\hfill & & & \cosh^{-1} x=\text{arccosh } x=\ln(x+\sqrt{x^2-1})\hfill \\ \tanh^{-1} x=\text{arctanh } x=\frac{1}{2}\ln\big(\frac{1+x}{1-x}\big)\hfill & & & \coth^{-1} x=\text{arccot } x=\frac{1}{2}\ln\big(\frac{x+1}{x-1}\big)\hfill \\ \text{sech}^{-1} x=\text{arcsech } x=\ln\big(\frac{1+\sqrt{1-x^2}}{x}\big)\hfill & & & \text{csch}^{-1} x=\text{arccsch } x=\ln\big(\frac{1}{x}+\frac{\sqrt{1+x^2}}{|x|}\big)\hfill \end{array}]
	p Let’s look at how to derive the first equation. The others follow similarly. Suppose #[+m y=\sinh^{-1} x]. Then, #[+m x=\sinh y] and, by the definition of the hyperbolic sine function, #[+m x=\frac{e^y-e^{−y}}{2}]. Therefore,  #[+m e^y-2x-e^{−y}=0]
	p Multiplying this equation by #[+m e^y], we obtain  #[+m e^{2y}-2xe^y-1=0]
	p This can be solved like a quadratic equation, with the solution  #[+m e^y=\large \frac{2x \pm \sqrt{4x^2+4}}{2} \normalsize =x \pm \sqrt{x^2+1}]
	p Since #[+m e^y>0], the only solution is the one with the positive sign. Applying the natural logarithm to both sides of the equation, we conclude that  #[+m y=\ln(x+\sqrt{x^2+1})]
	h5 Example: Evaluating Inverse Hyperbolic Functions
	p Evaluate each of the following expressions
	p #[+m \sinh^{-1}(2)] #[+m \tanh^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)]  Show Solution
	p #[+m \sinh^{-1}(2)=\ln(2+\sqrt{2^2+1})=\ln(2+\sqrt{5}) \approx 1.4436]
	p #[+m \tanh^{-1}(\frac{1}{4})=\frac{1}{2}\ln(\frac{1+1/4}{1-1/4})=\frac{1}{2}\ln(\frac{5/4}{3/4})=\frac{1}{2}\ln(\frac{5}{3}) \approx 0.2554]
	h5 Try It
	p Evaluate #[+m \tanh^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)].  Hint
	p Use the definition of #[+m \tanh^{-1} x] and simplify.  Show Solution
	p #[+m \frac{1}{2}\ln(3) \approx 0.5493].
